In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims September as Prostate Cancer Awareness Month. He highlights that although the mortality rate of prostate cancer has decreased in the past decade, it is still the second leading cause of cancer deaths among men in the United States. He emphasizes the importance of finding better ways to prevent, detect, and treat prostate cancer. The exact causes of prostate cancer are unknown, but factors such as age, race, and family history may increase the risk. The article encourages men to talk to their doctors about risk factors, prevention, and screenings. The government, through agencies like the National Cancer Institute, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and the Department of Defense, is investing in research to reduce the burden of prostate cancer. The Affordable Care Act also addresses the specific needs of individuals fighting cancer. The proclamation calls on all citizens, organizations, and businesses to participate in activities that raise awareness and prevent prostate cancer.